<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870727-0046 </DOCNO><HL> Litton Unit ChosenTo Repair FrigateHit in Gulf Attack</HL><DD> 07/27/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> LIT TRW RTN BA ROK GD EMRDEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF) </IN><DATELINE> WASHINGTON  </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Navy selected Litton Industries Inc.'s Ingalls Shipbuilding unit to perform repairs on the USS Stark, the frigate hit in May by an Iraqi missile fired in the Persian Gulf.    The contract will be awarded in coming months after the Navy performs a top-to-bottom inspection of the damage caused by the attack, in which 37 crewmen died. Sources estimate that the repair job could cost as much as $50 million. The bulk of the work will be performed in Mayport, Fla., the Stark's home port.    In other Pentagon contract actions, TRW Inc. received an $87.7 million Army job for development of a battlefield command and control system.    Boeing Co. was awarded a $62.3 million Air Force contract for B-1B aircraft avionics maintenance equipment.    Raytheon Co. won Army contracts totaling $28.7 million for Hawk and Patriot missile services.    Rockwell International Corp. was issued a $22.5 million Air Force contract for B-1B aircraft equipment.    General Dynamics Corp. received contracts totaling $18.3 million for M1 tank support for the Army and F-16 aircraft repairs for the Air Force.    Emerson Electric Co. was awarded a $14.3 million Army contract for armored vehicle equipment.    Scientific Applications International Corp. received a $13.8 million Navy contract for missile test range equipment. </TEXT></DOC>